Comparator ==>

1.uses method compare
2. part of java.util package
3. Collections.sort(list,comparator)
4. defines custom or multiple orderings for objects
5. Compare(T o1,T o2)
6.Can provide multiple sorting orders.
7.Negative if 01 < 02, zero if 01==02, positive if 01 > 02.
8. it works with wrapper classes only


in arrays=> Arrays.sort(booleans, (b1, b2) -> <any wrapper class>.compare(b1, b2));
eg:-Arrays.sort(booleans, (b1, b2) -> Boolean.compare(b1, b2));

0r for classes in array form 

Arrays.sort(people, new Comparator<Person>() {
    @Override
    public int compare(Person p1, Person p2) {
        int nameCompare = p1.getName().compareTo(p2.getName());
        if (nameCompare != 0) {
            return nameCompare;
        } else {
            return p2.getAge().compareTo(p1.getAge()); // Reverse comparison for age
        }
    }
});

Comparable ==>

1.uses method compareTo
2.part of java.lang package
3.Collections . sort (list) ;
4.Defines the natural ordering of objects.
5.compareTo(T o)
6.Provides only one natural sorting order.
7.Negative if this < o, zero if this==o, positive if this > o.
